1290–after 20 September 1361":"1290–after 20 September 1361","1285–1382":"1285–1382","1314–1363":"1314–1363","1290–1361":"1290–1361","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","after 20 September 1361":"after 20 September 1361","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Allington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): habitational name from any of at least nine different places called Allington, two in Kent, three in Wiltshire, and one each in Dorset, Devon, Hampshire, and Lincolnshire. These have different origins: those in Devon, Wiltshire near Chippenham, and Kent near Maidstone are from the Old English personal name <i>Ælla</i> + <i>-ingtūn</i> meaning ‘Ælla's farm’; those in Dorset, Wiltshire near Devizes, and Lincolnshire are named with Old English <i>ætheling</i> ‘prince' + <i>tūn</i>, meaning ‘settlement of the prince’; those in Hampshire and Wiltshire near Amesbury are from the Old English personal name <i>Ealda</i> + <i>tūn</i>; and the one in Kent near Lenham is from the Old English personal name <i>Æthelnōth</i> + <i>-ingtūn</i>, meaning ‘Æthelnōth's farm’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Paulina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of the Late Latin name <i>Paulinus</i>, a derivative of <i>Paulus</i> (  see  Paul  ). It was borne by several minor early martyrs."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Grace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the abstract noun (via Old French, from Latin <i>gratia</i>), this name occurs occasionally in the 15th century, and by the 1540s was among the most popular girls' names in some parishes. It has always been particularly popular in Scotland and northern England (borne, for example, by  Grace Darling , the lighthouse keeper's daughter whose heroism in  1838 , saving sailors in a storm, caught the popular imagination). In more recent times it was famous as the name of the actress  Grace Kelly  (  1928–82 ), who became  Princess Grace  of Monaco. In Ireland it is used as an Anglicized form of   Gráinne   ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":47,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Paulina Grace de Allington was born in 1290, in Cambridgeshire, England. She married Sir John Wimpole de Gras in 1313, in Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died after 20 September 1361, in England."},"et":{"1290–after 20 September 1361":"1290–pärast 20. septembrit 1361","1285–1382":"1285–1382","1314–1363":"1314–1363","1290–1361":"1290–1361","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","after 20 September 1361":"pärast 20. septembrit 1361","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–after 20 September 1361":"1290–20. syyskuuta 1361 jälkeen","1285–1382":"1285–1382","1314–1363":"1314–1363","1290–1361":"1290–1361","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","after 20 September 1361":"20. syyskuuta 1361 jälkeen","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Wimpole, Cambridgeshire, England, Unite